Multiple Inheritance
-> not allowed in java because if same field name is passed from both parent that would cause ambiguity.
-> with help of Interfaces we can achieve Multiple Inheritance.

Access types for class
-> classes can have only two types: public, default
-> default are Package Private

Access Types
-> By default fields in class are package private 
-> Private only accesable in class
-> Public accesable anywhere
-> protected can be accesable anywhere by child classes or in same package
-> package Private only accesable in package

Constructor
-> Private constructor 
    -> when we want to have a singleton class so we want to restrict object creation.
    -> when we want to create a Utility Type of class everything static.
    -> For Enums constructors are private because objects are fixed constant no more are intended.
-> protected
    -> In abstract classes -> constructor should be protected because its object can't be created so only child class that extend this will call this,
     when creating child class object base class constructor will be called where protected is enough no need of public.

Final(constant)
-> Variable: can not be changed
-> Methods: can not be overidden
-> class: can not be extended
-> constructor: not allowed because constructor can't be modified or inherited by default so no need

Interfaces
-> Methods: By default are public
    -> abstract: when we don't specify anything method will be of this type
    -> static: it belongs to interface not implementing class so can only be called by interface name.
    -> default: They have implementation and belongs to implementation class
        => usecase: when there are alot of classes implementing a interface and you want to add a method then it is tedious task to add it's implementation in all the classes.
-> variables: By default are public static Final
    -> Recommended to be called with Interface not implementing class because it belongs to interface

Diff B/W Interface and abstaract class
-> abstract class have instance varibles for there initialization it have constructor, Interfaces don't have constructor
-> we can implement multiple interfaces for a class, but it is not possible for abstract class.

Inner class
-> Member Inner class:
    -> when the classes are related we can have a inner class that will act as member of the outer class and can access the other members, this can save the pain of creating 
    another class and having a referance of outer class to establish relation.
    -> it belongs to the outer class instance
    -> it's object will not be created automatically but needed to be created in out constructor or by using outer instance.
-> static inner class:
    -> It belongs to the outer class rather than it's instance
    -> generally used for grouping related classes together
-> anonymous inner class
    -> when we want to create instance of implementation class of a interface/abstactClass without creating implementation class.
    -> for one time use purpose.
-> Local Inner class
    -> It is created inside method of a outer class
    -> It is tightly coupled with that method as we don't want to use it anywhere else.
    -> It can use other members of inclosing object. 

